veals the forms of social inequality produced by shifts in the economy. No longer working for the common good as defined by the socialist state, service workers are catering to the individual desires of consumers. This economic transition ultimately affords a unique opportunity to investigate the possibilities and current limits for better working conditions for the young women who are enabling the development of capitalism in China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEqualityxChinaxChina. 0aEqualityzChina. 0aSex role in the work environmentxChina. 0aSex role in the work environmentzChina. 0aWomen service industries workersxChina. 0aWomen service industries workerszChina. 0aWomenxEmploymentxChina. 0aWomenxEmploymentzChina. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxChina. 0aWomenzChinaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477835040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804778350423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804778350.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles